        "content": "This psalm is traditionally and historically attributed to David. Conservative scholars such as E.J. Young and Merrill Unger affirm the accuracy of the Masoretic superscription, noting that the internal evidence of the psalm fits a king facing organized, deceitful opposition. The term Nehiloth in the heading has been the subject of much debate among conservative linguists. Keil and Delitzsch argue it refers to wind instruments, specifically flutes, which would provide a somber yet melodic accompaniment to David’s morning plea. The historical setting is likely a time of political unrest, possibly during the Sauline persecutions or the early stages of Absalom’s rebellion, where the integrity of the King’s speech and the sanctity of the Tabernacle were central themes."
