        "content": "The superscription identifies this psalm as a Shiggaion of David which he sang unto the Lord concerning the words of Cush the Benjamite. While the identity of Cush is not explicitly stated in the historical books of Samuel, conservative scholars like Matthew Henry and Albert Barnes suggest he was a follower of Saul or perhaps a pseudonym for Saul himself, representing the Benjaminite faction that viewed David as a traitor. John Gill notes that the term Cush signifies an Ethiopian, potentially used as a metaphor for the blackness of this enemy's heart or his unchangeable malice. The setting is one of intense personal slander and physical pursuit, likely during the period of David's exile when he was falsely accused of seeking Saul’s life."
