        "content": "The Davidic authorship of Psalm 11 is firmly supported by the Masoretic superscription and internal evidence reflecting the life of the shepherd-king. Conservative scholars such as Franz Delitzsch and Charles Spurgeon identify the setting as the early period of David’s life, specifically during the Sauline persecutions. Unlike the rebellion of Absalom where David actually fled Jerusalem, this Psalm captures a moment when David is being urged to flee by well-meaning but fearful advisors. The historical backdrop is one of a deteriorating court where justice is perverted and the king’s enemies are operating with clandestine malice, forcing the righteous to choose between pragmatic retreat and spiritual steadfastness."
