        "title": "Historical Background",
        "content": "The authorship of Psalm 12 is traditionally and internally attributed to David. Conservative scholars such as H.C. Leupold and J.A. Alexander affirm this Davidic origin, noting the superscription mentions the Chief Musician and the Sheminith. The term Sheminith likely refers to an eight-stringed instrument or a musical direction for a lower, bass octave, suggesting a somber or grave tone. While no specific event in David's life is cited, the historical backdrop is clearly a period of extreme moral decay and social apostasy. John Calvin suggests the Psalm reflects a time when truth was systematically suppressed, similar to the periods of Saul's persecution or the betrayal of Absalom, where loyal friends became scarce and flattery became a tool of political survival."
