        "content": "The Psalm is structured through synthetic parallelism, where the second line of a couplet expands or completes the thought of the first. An example is found in verse 2, where the granting of the heart's desire is further defined as not withholding the request of the lips. The poem also utilizes a significant Inclusio, beginning in verse 1 with praise for God’s strength and concluding in verse 13 with a corporate call for God to be exalted in His own strength. A distinct literary shift occurs at verse 8; while verses 1 through 7 address God regarding the king, verses 8 through 12 address the king himself, predicting his triumph over his foes. This shift highlights the king as the earthly agent of divine judgment."
