        "title": "Brief Exposition",
        "content": "Psalm 21 provides a theological bridge between the petition of the suffering servant and the triumph of the exalted Lord. The first seven verses focus on the prevenient grace of God. The king is blessed not because of his merit, but because God prevents him with the blessings of goodness. This indicates that God’s favor often anticipates our needs before we even voice them. The mention of the crown and eternal life transitions the reader’s mind from the earthly David to the heavenly Christ, whose kingdom is without end. In the second movement (verses 8 to 12), the tone shifts from celebration to solemnity. The King is not only a recipient of grace but also a dispenser of justice. His hand will find out all his enemies, and his judgment will be as inescapable as a fiery furnace. This section serves as a warning that to reject the King is to invite the consuming fire of the Most High. The Psalm concludes in verse 13 by returning the focus to Yahweh. All the glory of the king, the victory of the army, and the stability of the nation are attributed to the strength of God alone. For the conservative believer, this Psalm is a call to rejoice in the current reign of Christ while maintaining a holy fear of the judgment that His return will bring."
