        "title": "Historical Background",
        "content": "The superscription attributes this Psalm to David and directs it to the Chief Musician set to the tune of Ayelet Ha-Shachar, translated as The Hind of the Morning. Conservative scholars such as Franz Delitzsch argue that while the Psalm may have roots in Davidic suffering, the language far exceeds any documented historical event in David's life, such as the persecution by Saul or the rebellion of Absalom. Traditional conservative thought, supported by Charles Spurgeon, maintains that David wrote this under the immediate inspiration of the Holy Spirit, functioning as a prophet. The historical setting is the shadow of the cross, viewed through the Spirit of Christ which was in the prophets. The title Hind of the Morning is often interpreted by older scholars like John Gill as a reference to the morning of the resurrection or the innocence of the sufferer hunted by dogs."
