        "content": "Psalm 24 is traditionally attributed to David. Conservative scholars such as Franz Delitzsch and Charles Spurgeon link its composition to the momentous occasion of the Ark of the Covenant being brought from the house of Obed-edom to Mount Zion, as recorded in 2 Samuel 6 and 1 Chronicles 15. The psalm serves as a liturgical processional celebrating the entry of Yahweh into His sanctuary. It marks the transition of Jerusalem from a Jebusite stronghold to the spiritual center of the covenant people."
