        "title": "Christ in the Old Testament",
        "content": "While David appeals to his integrity, no fallen human can claim this perfectly. Therefore, Psalm 26 is ultimately the prayer of the Great High Priest, Jesus Christ.\n\nChrist is the only One who \"walked in His integrity\" without a single stumble (verse 1).\n\nJesus is the true Worshiper who perfectly loved the \"habitation of God's house\" (verse 8), demonstrated when He cleansed the Temple.\n\nOn the Cross, Christ was \"gathered with sinners\" (the opposite of the plea in verse 9) so that His people would not have to be. He took the place of the \"men of falsehood\" so that they might receive His \"integrity.\"\n\nThe \"even place\" or \"level ground\" in verse 12 represents the standing of the believer in Christ, where the foot is made firm by the imputed righteousness of the Savior.",
