        "title": "Brief Exposition",
        "content": "Psalm 36 begins by looking into the abyss of the human heart where sin acts as a false god. The wicked man has reached a state where he no longer fears God and has lost the ability to detect his own guilt. He plots evil even in the silence of his bed. However, the Psalmist suddenly shifts his gaze from the darkness of the heart to the brightness of the heavens. He describes God's mercy, faithfulness, righteousness, and judgments using the grandest scales of the natural world. This transition teaches that the only remedy for the observation of rampant evil is a renewed vision of God's character. God is not just a distant judge; He is a provider who invites His people to feast on the abundance of His house and drink from the river of His pleasures. The Psalm concludes with a petition for the continuation of this grace toward the righteous and a prophetic glimpse of the ultimate downfall of the workers of iniquity, who are cast down and unable to rise."
