      {
        "title": "Jewish Tradition",
        "content": "In Midrash Tehillim, Jewish sages emphasize the connection between the land mentioned in this psalm and the world to come. Rashi, the premier medieval commentator, interprets the land primarily as the Land of Israel, suggesting that the inheritance promised to the humble is a physical and spiritual dwelling in the presence of the Shekhinah. The Talmud (m. Kiddushin) draws from verse 25 to discuss God’s providence, noting that while the righteous may suffer, they are never truly forsaken by the Almighty. Jewish tradition also highlights the contrast between the prosperity of Esau and the eventual inheritance of Jacob as a historical archetype for this psalm."
      },
      {
        "title": "Brief Exposition",
        "content": "Psalm 37 is a masterpiece of biblical pedagogy, designed to calm the anxious heart of the believer who looks at the world and sees the ungodly flourishing. The psalm opens with the command to fret not. This is not a suggestion but a spiritual discipline. The psalmist provides a series of imperatives: Trust in the Lord, Delight in the Lord, Commit thy way, and Rest in the Lord.\n\nThe middle section of the psalm addresses the reality of conflict. The wicked draw their swords to slay the poor, but the psalmist declares that their own swords shall enter their own hearts. This reflects the biblical principle of lex talionis, where the evil intended for others returns upon the perpetrator.\n\nThe crux of the psalm is the concept of inheritance. While the wicked appear to own everything, they actually possess nothing of eternal value. In contrast, the righteous may have little (verse 16), but that little is better than the riches of many wicked because it is accompanied by the favor of God.\n\nThe psalm concludes with a focus on the end of a man's life. The wicked may spread themselves like a green bay tree, but they suddenly vanish. The righteous man, however, has a future. The salvation of the righteous is of the Lord; He is their strength in the time of trouble. The final word is one of refuge, reminding the believer that safety is found only in the Lord."
      }
