      {
        "title": "Jewish Tradition",
        "content": "Rashi, the preeminent Jewish commentator, interprets the miry clay in verse 2 as a metaphor for the exile of the Jewish people or David’s personal struggles with sin and its consequences. In the Babylonian Talmud (Sotah 10b), the roll of the book mentioned in verse 7 is identified as the scroll of the Torah, specifically the requirements placed upon a king to remain humble and obedient. Midrash Tehillim connects the new song in verse 3 to the future song that will be sung at the final redemption of Israel, viewing David’s personal deliverance as a microcosm of the nation's eventual salvation."
      },
      {
        "title": "Brief Exposition",
        "content": "Psalm 40 opens with a powerful testimony of patience and divine intervention. David describes being pulled from a pit of noise and sinking mud, a metaphor for a life-threatening crisis or deep spiritual depression. God’s response was to set David’s feet on a rock and give him a new song. This deliverance leads David to a profound theological realization: God is not primarily interested in the blood of bulls or goats. Instead, God has bored his ears—He has made David a willing and attentive servant. This points to the truth that true worship is the surrender of the heart and the delight in doing God's will.\n\nHowever, the tone shifts abruptly in the second half of the psalm. David finds himself surrounded by evils that are more numerous than the hairs of his head. His heart fails him, and he cries out for God to make haste. This shift reminds the believer that one victory does not mean the end of all battles. The foundation of the prayer in the second half is the character of God proven in the first half. Ultimately, the psalm transcends David. The author of Hebrews applies these words to Jesus Christ, explaining that when Christ came into the world, He took these verses upon His lips. He is the only one who truly delighted in God’s law within His heart and whose sacrifice of Himself once for all put an end to the need for legalistic ritual. For the Christian, Psalm 40 is a call to look at the work of Christ, our Rock, and find the strength to offer our own lives as sacrifices of obedience."
      }
