        "title": "Scholarly Voices",
        "content": "1. Charles Spurgeon notes in The Treasury of David that the psalmist moves from the miseries of earth to the selections of heaven by appealing to the highest court.\n\n2. John Calvin emphasizes that when we are overwhelmed by the world, we must take refuge in the light of God which shines through His promises.\n\n3. Matthew Henry points out that the psalmist identifies God as his strength even when he feels cast off, showing that faith survives even when feelings of comfort fail.\n\n4. Alexander Maclaren highlights the transition from the soul talking to itself in despair to the soul talking to God in hope.\n\n5. Franz Delitzsch observes that the request for light and truth is a request for the fulfillment of the Word of God, as these attributes ensure the preservation of the covenant.\n\n6. Timothy Keller continues the discipline of Psalm 42 by asking God to send light and truth when emotion cannot lead itself home. Psalm 43 teaches that the goal of deliverance is not mere relief but restored worship at God's altar.\n\n7. D. Martyn Lloyd-Jones continues the cure for the downcast soul by showing that light and truth must lead the believer back to worship. The answer to inner turmoil is not self-absorption but return to God's altar and praise.\n\n8. Alec Motyer highlights the shared refrain with Psalm 42 and the prayer for light and truth, showing that despondency is healed by God's guidance back to worship and inviting the soul to hope its way toward the altar.\n\n9. John Stott continues the same cure for spiritual depression by asking for God's light and truth to lead the worshiper home, showing that renewed hope is tied to restored communion with God.",
