        "title": "Scholarly Voices",
        "content": "1. John Calvin emphasizes that the chief trial for David was not the external threat of the sword, but the internal wound caused by the breach of friendship. He argues that this psalm teaches believers how to bring their most chaotic emotions before God rather than nursing them in secret.\n\n2. Charles Spurgeon highlights the prophetic nature of the text, noting that the sorrow of David is but a shadow of the sorrow of the Son of Man. He famously remarks that the church house is the place where the worst wounds are often inflicted, just as David was betrayed by one who walked to the house of God in his company.\n\n3. Matthew Henry focuses on the practical application of verse 22, noting that the command to cast thy burden upon the Lord involves both the duty of prayer and the grace of faith. He asserts that while God may not remove the burden immediately, He promises to sustain the person carrying it.\n\n4. Alexander Maclaren points out the psychological realism of the psalm, describing the transition from the desire to flee to the wilderness to the determination to stay and pray. He views the wilderness as a place of temporary refuge but the Lord as an eternal habitation.\n\n5. Keil and Delitzsch focus on the linguistic nuances of the Hebrew, particularly the term for distraction or restlessness in verse 2, suggesting David’s mind was tossing like a sea in a storm due to the conspiracy.\n\n6. Timothy Keller shows that Psalm 55 gives words for the uniquely bitter wound of betrayal by a close companion. Its pastoral center is the invitation to cast the burden on the Lord, trusting that He can sustain what the heart cannot carry.\n\n7. Alec Motyer highlights the wound of betrayal by a familiar friend, showing that public danger is sharpened by private treachery and inviting the burdened believer to cast the load on the Lord.",
