        "content": "Psalm 58 is traditionally attributed to King David and is designated as a Michtam, a term often associated with a golden psalm or an inscription of deep significance. Conservative scholars such as Gleason Archer and E.J. Young maintain its Davidic origin, likely originating during the period of Saul's unjust reign or the burgeoning rebellion of Absalom. The superscription includes the phrase Al-taschith, meaning Do Not Destroy, which connects it to other Davidic psalms written during times of extreme personal peril and national moral decay. The historical setting is one of judicial crisis, where those appointed to uphold the Law of Moses had become the primary instruments of its violation."
