        "content": "In the Midrash Tehillim, the Jewish sages emphasize the comparison between David's enemies and hungry dogs, noting that while dogs are naturally scavengers, these men were unnaturally cruel in their pursuit of the innocent. Rashi, the premier medieval commentator, identifies the dogs in verse 6 as the guards of Saul who were sent to intercept David at dawn. The Talmud (Berakhot 4a) discusses the timing of David's prayers, linking his morning song in verse 16 to his practice of rising at midnight to study Torah and praise God, ensuring that his praise preceded the dawn. Radak (Rabbi David Kimhi) interprets the Psalm as having a dual application: David's immediate struggle and the future exile of the Jewish people, where the heathens surround the nation like howling dogs."
