        "title": "Brief Exposition",
        "content": "Psalm 64 moves from the atmosphere of a clandestine conspiracy to the public arena of divine victory. David begins by asking God to preserve his life from a specific kind of enemy: the one who uses words as weapons. These enemies do not fight in the open but sharpen their tongues like swords and hide in secret places to shoot their arrows of slander at the innocent. They are characterized by an inward depth of malice, encouraging one another in evil and believing that their plots are hidden from every eye.\n\nThe turning point is verse 7, which introduces the sudden intervention of God. While the wicked were busy aiming their arrows, God aimed his. The ironic climax occurs when their own tongues fall upon them, meaning that their own words and schemes become the weight that destroys them. This judgment is so clear and so public that it causes all people to fear and declare that it is the work of God. The psalm concludes with a call to the righteous to be glad in the Lord and to find their glory in his justice. It teaches that while the plots of man are deep, the judgment of God is deeper and swifter."
