        "title": "Jewish Tradition",
        "content": "In Jewish tradition, Rashi explains that this Psalm was separated from Psalm 40 to be used specifically by those in sudden, dire straits. Rashi emphasizes that David speaks not only for himself but for the entire nation of Israel in exile, crying out for the end of the long night of suffering. Midrash Tehillim notes that David asks God not to be late because if God delays, the strength of the petitioner might fail entirely. The Talmud in Tractate Berakhot discusses the importance of brief, fervent prayers in moments of danger, using the spirit of this Psalm as a model. The use of the word Heach (Aha!) in verse 3 is noted by Jewish commentators as the specific sound of malicious joy that the enemies of Zion make, which God is asked to turn back upon them as shame."
