        "title": "Brief Exposition",
        "content": "Psalm 70 is the cry of a man who is at the absolute end of his tether. David begins not with a formal address but with a gasp for help: Make haste, O God, to deliver me! This is the prayer of someone who is sinking. The central portion of the Psalm deals with the two groups of people present in every spiritual conflict: those who seek the believers soul and those who seek God. David asks that the mockers be paralyzed by their own shame, not out of personal spite, but because they are mocking the God whom David represents. In contrast, he prays that those who love Gods salvation would have their mouths filled with praise, saying, Let God be magnified! The Psalm concludes with a stark self-assessment. David calls himself poor and needy. In the Hebrew context, this refers to more than just material poverty; it describes the anawim—the humble, afflicted ones who have no helper but God. By ending with the titles My Help and My Deliverer, David anchors his frantic plea in the solid character of Yahweh. He acknowledges that while he is in a hurry, God is the sovereign Master of time. He submits his urgency to the only One capable of acting upon it."
