        "content": "1. Derek Kidner observes that the opening word why indicates a faith that is baffled but still seeks an audience with God rather than turning away in apostasy.\n\n2. Charles Spurgeon, in The Treasury of David, points out that the enemies of God think they are destroying the work of men, but they are actually attacking the dwelling place of the Most High, which ensures their eventual judgment.\n\n3. John Calvin emphasizes that the psalmists primary concern is the glory of Gods Name, arguing that when the Church is in ruins, the honor of God is at stake before the nations.\n\n4. H.C. Leupold argues that the reference to the absence of prophets in verse 9 specifically marks the transition period of the Babylonian exile when the prophetic voice was temporarily silenced to test the peoples reliance on the written Word.\n\n5. G. Campbell Morgan notes that the psalmists appeal to the day and night and the seasons in verses 16 and 17 serves as a legal argument that the God who maintains the natural order must also be faithful to His moral and covenantal order.\n\n6. Timothy Keller shows that Psalm 74 brings devastated worship into God's presence by appealing to His own name, covenant, and past victories. The ruined sanctuary is not the end of faith, because the Creator-King still owns the day and night.\n\n7. Alec Motyer points out that temple ruins are held before the Creator who divided sea and day from night, showing that present devastation must be prayed in light of God's ancient power and covenant name.",
