        "content": "Psalm 80 is traditionally attributed to Asaph and belongs to the second book of the Psalter. Conservative scholars such as H.C. Leupold and Derek Kidner suggest the historical setting aligns with the period following the Assyrian destruction of the Northern Kingdom in 722 BC. The explicit mention of the tribes of Ephraim, Benjamin, and Manasseh indicates a focus on the Josephite tribes of the North. E.W. Hengstenberg argues that the psalm may have been composed during the reign of King Hezekiah or King Josiah as they reached out to the remnants of the northern tribes to invite them back into spiritual unity with Jerusalem. The atmosphere is one of national lament, written from the perspective of a people who feel the stinging rebuke of God's silence and the devastation of their borders."
