        "title": "Jewish Tradition",
        "content": "Rashi interprets the opening address to the Shepherd of Israel as a specific plea for God to remember the wilderness wanderings when He led Joseph like a flock through the pillar of cloud and fire. The Midrash Tehillim connects the three mentioned tribes to their historical positions behind the Ark of the Covenant during the desert marches, suggesting the psalmist is asking for a new exodus-level manifestation of power. In the Talmud, specifically Sukkah 45a and 45b, the refrain regarding the shining of God's face is linked to the Priestly Blessing of Numbers 6, emphasizing that Israel's survival depends entirely upon the divine countenance. Rashi also notes that the vine mentioned in verse 8 refers to the displacement of the seven nations of Canaan to make room for the holy planting of Israel."
