        "content": "Psalm 82 is traditionally attributed to Asaph, a prominent Levite singer and prophet during the reign of King David. Conservative scholars such as Gleason Archer and H.C. Leupold date the composition to the monarchic period, though some suggest it was preserved as a prophetic warning for later generations of Israelite leaders. The historical setting involves a crisis of justice where those appointed to reflect God’s character—whether human judges in Israel or spiritual principalities over nations—had fallen into systemic corruption. The psalm addresses a time when the moral foundations of the earth were perceived to be crumbling due to the failure of authority figures to protect the vulnerable."
