        "content": "1. Charles Spurgeon (The Treasury of David) emphasizes that the psalmist’s ability to address God as the God of my salvation in the opening verse is a triumph of faith, proving that grace can exist in the heart even when joy is absent from the life.\n\n2. John Calvin notes that Heman’s persistent prayer—crying out day and night—demonstrates that the godly do not cease to seek God even when they feel He has become their enemy. Calvin views this as a supreme test of the believer's endurance.\n\n3. Derek Kidner observes that the psalm provides a voice for those in clinical depression or terminal suffering, legitimizing their experience within the canon of Scripture without forcing a superficial happy ending.\n\n4. Matthew Henry points out that the psalmist’s complaints are directed to God, not against Him. This distinction is vital in conservative hermeneutics, as it transforms a complaint into an act of worship.\n\n5. Keil and Delitzsch argue that the mention of being shut up and unable to come forth (verse 8) is a literal reference to the quarantine laws of Leviticus 13, suggesting the physical reality of leprosy as the backdrop for the spiritual agony.\n\n6. Timothy Keller highlights Psalm 88 as proof that Scripture gives room for prayers that end in darkness. The absence of visible resolution does not make the prayer faithless; the sufferer still speaks to the God of salvation.\n\n7. Alec Motyer highlights the absence of a bright ending, showing that Scripture gives faithful language even for unresolved darkness and inviting sufferers to keep addressing the God of salvation when comfort is hidden.",
