        "content": "1. The Man of Sorrows: Psalm 88 is the most vivid Old Testament portrayal of the inner emotional life of Christ during His passion. Heman’s darkness prefigures the three hours of darkness over the land at Calvary.\n\n2. The Great High Priest: Because this psalm is in the Bible, it serves as a record that Christ, our High Priest, has entered into the absolute lowest state of human experience, including the feeling of being unheard by the Father.\n\n3. The Substitutionary Sufferer: The terrors and wrath mentioned in verse 16 are those that should have fallen on the sinner, but were taken by Christ. He became the one counted with those who go down to the pit so that believers might not have to.\n\n4. The Faithfulness of the Son: Just as Heman continues to pray despite the silence, Christ continued to entrust Himself to Him who judges righteously, even when the light of the Father's countenance was momentarily withdrawn.",
