        "title": "Jewish Tradition",
        "content": "In the Talmudic tradition, Psalm 96 is often linked to the Messianic age. Rashi, the premier Jewish commentator, highlights the significance of the New Song (Shir Chadash). He notes that in the Hebrew language, most songs are referred to in the feminine form (shirah), which can imply the weakness or the pain of a woman in labor, suggesting that previous deliverances were followed by further troubles. However, the New Song here is masculine (shir), representing a final, permanent redemption that will never be followed by exile or sorrow. The Midrash Tehillim connects this psalm to the period after the war of Gog and Magog, viewing it as the ultimate anthem of a world finally at peace under the sovereignty of the Almighty."
