        "content": "Psalm 96 serves as a powerful bridge between the worship of Israel and the mission to the world. It begins with a vibrant call to sing a new song, which conservative scholars interpret as a response to a new intervention of God in history—ultimately the work of Christ. The psalmist does not allow for a private faith; the glory of Yahweh must be declared among the nations. This is a direct challenge to the polytheism of the ancient world and the secularism of the modern world. The psalmist ruthlessly mocks idols as elilim (worthless things), contrasting them with the God who spoke the heavens into existence.\n\nThe middle section of the psalm (verses 7-9) anticipates the gathering of all tribes into the presence of God. It emphasizes that true worship requires an offering and the beauty of holiness, pointing toward the internal transformation required by the Gospel. Finally, the psalm reaches a crescendo by announcing the reign of God. This is not a cause for fear for the righteous, but for joy. Even inanimate nature—the sea, the fields, and the trees—is depicted as being in a state of ecstatic worship because the Judge is coming. For the conservative believer, this is the hope of the Parousia: the day when the King returns to set all things right and rule the world with the truth of His Word."
