        "title": "Brief Exposition",
        "content": "Psalm 99 is a call to recognize the moral absolute of the universe: the holiness of God. It begins with the command for the earth to tremble and the people to shake. This is not a request but a theological necessity when the Creator sits upon His throne. The first movement focuses on God's greatness in Zion, being high above all peoples. The second movement shifts to the character of His reign. Unlike earthly tyrants, this King loves justice and establishes equity. He is not just powerful; He is right. The final movement provides comfort by reminding the reader that this holy God is approachable through mediation. By citing Moses, Aaron, and Samuel, the psalmist shows that God hears the cries of those who call upon His name. However, holiness is not compromised for the sake of relationship; verse 8 reminds us that He is a God who forgives but also an avenger of sinful inventions. The psalm concludes where it must: at the holy hill, with a final declaration that the Lord our God is holy. This requires the believer to live in a state of perpetual, reverent worship."
