        "content": "1. Charles Spurgeon, in The Treasury of David, refers to this as the Old Hundredth and states that it contains a gospel spirit that invites all nations to the joy of the Lord. He emphasizes that serving God with gladness is the mark of a true believer.\n\n2. John Calvin highlights that the knowledge mentioned in verse 3 is not merely intellectual but an experiential recognition of God’s sovereignty. He notes that by stating God made us and not we ourselves, the psalmist strikes at the root of human pride.\n\n3. Alexander Maclaren observes the progression of the worshiper from the wide world in verse 1 to the specific gates and courts in verse 4, showing that universal sovereignty leads to personal intimacy.\n\n4. Derek Kidner points out the significance of the word Truth in verse 5, noting it refers to God's faithfulness to His covenant, which remains unshakable from generation to generation.\n\n5. Matthew Henry remarks that the call to be thankful is a call to a pleasant duty, for God is a Master who desires His servants to be happy in His presence.\n\n6. Timothy Keller treats Psalm 100 as cheerful covenant worship. The call to serve with gladness rests on belonging: the Lord made us, shepherds us, and receives thanksgiving because His steadfast love endures.\n\n7. Alec Motyer highlights the simplicity of joyful service grounded in belonging, showing that thanksgiving flows from being made and shepherded by the Lord and inviting the whole earth into covenant praise.\n\n8. John Stott summarizes worship with joy, service, thanksgiving, and knowledge that the Lord is both God and good, grounding praise in His ownership, shepherd care, and enduring faithfulness.",
