      {
        "title": "Brief Outline",
        "content": "Theme: The Vow of the Godly King to Maintain Integrity in Private and Public Life.\n\n1. The Song of the King’s Standard (Verse 1).\n\n2. The Resolve for Personal Sanctification (Verses 2 through 4).\n\n3. The Selection of Godly Associates (Verses 5 through 7).\n\n4. The Execution of Judicial Justice (Verse 8)."
      },
      {
        "title": "Jewish Tradition",
        "content": "In Jewish tradition, Midrash Tehillim emphasizes that this psalm highlights the two attributes of God: Mercy (Chesed) and Judgment (Mishpat). The sages teach that David sought to sing to God regardless of whether he was experiencing kindness or discipline. Rashi interprets the phrase I will walk within my house in verse 2 as David’s commitment to be as righteous in his private chambers as he was in public, noting that a leader’s true character is revealed at home. The Talmud, specifically in Sotah 5a, cites verse 5 to explain that God cannot dwell in the same world as the person who possesses a haughty look and a proud heart, as pride effectively attempts to displace the Divine Presence."
      },
      {
        "title": "Brief Exposition",
        "content": "Psalm 101 provides a constitutional blueprint for godly leadership, beginning with the individual and extending to the state. David recognizes that he cannot demand of his subjects what he does not practice himself. Therefore, the psalm begins with a focus on the heart and the eyes. By vowing not to set worthless things before his eyes, David identifies the eyes as the gateway to the soul, a principle that remains vital for modern believers.\n\nThe scope then widens to the royal court. David understands that a leader is often judged by the character of his subordinates. He vows to silence the slanderer and dismiss the proud, ensuring that his administration is composed of the faithful of the land. The psalm concludes with a commitment to daily justice. Morning by morning, the king must act to preserve the holiness of the city. This daily diligence serves as a type of the final judgment, where the Great King will once and for all remove all workers of iniquity from His presence. For the conservative reader, Psalm 101 is both a conviction of our failures and a pointer toward the perfect reign of the Lord Jesus Christ."
      }
