      {
        "title": "Jewish Tradition",
        "content": "Jewish tradition holds Psalm 103 in high regard as a fundamental statement of the Thirteen Attributes of Mercy found in Exodus 34. Rashi, the preeminent medieval commentator, notes that the repetition of \"Bless the Lord, O my soul\" occurs five times in Psalms 103 and 104, which the Midrash Tehillim suggests corresponds to the five stages of the soul or the five worlds a person inhabits. Rashi specifically interprets the renewal of youth like an eagle as a reference to the annual molting of the eagle, which restores its vigor. The Talmud in Berakhot 10a compares the soul to God: just as God fills the world, the soul fills the body; just as God sees but is not seen, the soul sees but is not seen. Therefore, the soul is uniquely qualified to praise the One who formed it."
      },
      {
        "title": "Brief Exposition",
        "content": "Psalm 103 is a masterpiece of biblical theology that moves the believer from the internal recesses of the heart to the farthest reaches of the universe. David begins by commanding his \"soul\" and \"all that is within me\" to praise God, suggesting that worship is a volitional act of the will, not merely a feeling. He lists five benefits that cover the totality of human need: spiritual (forgiveness), physical (healing), legal (redemption), social (crowning), and existential (satisfaction).\n\nThe heart of the Psalm (verses 6-18) explores the \"Hesed\" or covenant-love of God. David reaches back to Exodus 33 and 34, where God revealed His name to Moses. He explains that God’s anger is slow and His mercy is vast. The metaphors used are spatial (height of heaven, distance of East from West) and relational (a father with his children). David acknowledges the \"dust\" of humanity—not as an excuse for sin, but as a reason for God’s pity.\n\nFinally, the Psalm expands its scope. What began as a solo becomes a symphony. David calls upon the angels, the heavenly hosts, and all of God's works in all places of His dominion to join the song. Yet, in a final stroke of poetic intimacy, David returns to where he started in the final sentence: \"Bless the Lord, O my soul.\" This indicates that while God is the King of the universe, He is most glorified when a single, redeemed soul recognizes His grace."
      }
