        "title": "Historical Background",
        "content": "Psalm 106 serves as the concluding anthem of Book IV of the Psalter. It is a historical psalm that mirrors the narrative of Psalm 105 but shifts the focus from Gods faithfulness to Israels persistent rebellion. Most conservative scholars, such as H.C. Leupold and J.A. Alexander, identify its composition as either late in the Davidic era or more likely during the early post-exilic period. Internal evidence in verse 47 suggests a community seeking gathering from among the nations, pointing toward the Babylonian captivity. However, the first and last verses appear in 1 Chronicles 16, which records the bringing of the Ark of the Covenant to Jerusalem, suggesting the themes were foundational to Davidic worship even if the final form was edited later. It is a national confession of sin, or a communal laments liturgy, designed to remind the covenant people that their survival is due entirely to the mercy of Yahweh and not their own merit."
