        "content": "1. C.H. Spurgeon in The Treasury of David calls this the Pearl of Psalms because it contains the absolute core of the gospel, including Christ's divinity, humanity, kingdom, and priesthood.\n\n2. John Calvin stresses that the session at the right hand does not denote a place but a function of supreme authority and the protection of the Church.\n\n3. Keil and Delitzsch argue that the oath in verse 4 is the climax of the psalm, indicating that the priesthood of Christ is not based on genealogy but on an eternal divine decree.\n\n4. H.C. Leupold interprets the drinking from the brook in verse 7 as a metaphor for the Messiahs unflagging energy and the fact that His victory requires no rest.\n\n5. O. Palmer Robertson emphasizes that this psalm provides the biblical-theological bridge between the Davidic covenant and the Melchizedekian priesthood, uniting the offices of King and Priest.\n\n6. Derek Kidner notes that verse 3 describes the willing people of the King as being like dew from the womb of the morning, suggesting both their vast number and their fresh, divine origin.\n\n7. Timothy Keller reads Psalm 110 as the clearest royal-priestly horizon of the Psalter. The king seated at God's right hand and appointed priest forever points beyond David to the victorious Christ who reigns and intercedes.\n\n8. Alec Motyer points out that kingship and priesthood are joined in one promised figure, showing that the Lord's Messiah conquers and intercedes and inviting faith in the Priest-King seated at God's right hand.",
