        "title": "Jewish Tradition",
        "content": "Early Jewish tradition, preserved in the Midrash Tehillim, initially recognized the messianic character of this psalm. However, in the post-Christian era, many Jewish commentators shifted their interpretations to counter Christian claims. Rashi, for instance, famously interprets my lord in verse 1 as referring to Abraham, suggesting the psalm celebrates his victory over the kings in Genesis 14. Despite this, the Babylonian Talmud in Sanhedrin 108b and Midrash Rabbah on Numbers retain threads of messianic application, particularly regarding the session at the right hand. The Qumran community (11QMelchizedek) viewed the figure of Melchizedek as a divine deliverer who would achieve atonement and judgment, echoing the psalms priestly and judicial themes."
