        "content": "1. Charles Spurgeon, in The Treasury of David, emphasizes that the works of the Lord are sought out by those who have pleasure in them, suggesting that the study of God is a delightful duty for the believer.\n\n2. John Calvin notes that the psalmist highlights the reliability of God’s covenant, asserting that God does not merely perform random acts of power but acts in accordance with His promised faithfulness.\n\n3. Alexander Maclaren observes the connection between Psalm 111 and 112, noting that Psalm 111 describes the character of the Master, while Psalm 112 describes the character of the servant who imitates Him.\n\n4. Derek Kidner points out that the word sought out in verse 2 implies a scientific or investigative rigor, suggesting that God’s works are deep and require meditation to be fully understood.\n\n5. Keil and Delitzsch argue that the term redemption in verse 9 refers to both the historical Exodus and the general concept of divine deliverance that is constant throughout Israel’s history.\n\n6. Timothy Keller highlights Psalm 111 as praise that studies the works of God carefully. Wonder is deepened, not diminished, by attention; the fear of the Lord begins when grace, righteousness, provision, and redemption are remembered with delight.\n\n7. Alec Motyer observes that the works of the Lord are studied by those who delight in them, showing that praise deepens through attention and inviting reverent wisdom rooted in redemption and provision.",
