        "title": "Brief Exposition",
        "content": "Psalm 117 serves as a theological explosive, shattering any notion of a localized or ethnic deity. In two short verses, the Psalmist commands the entire human race to recognize the sovereignty of the Lord. The motive for this praise is rooted in two pillars of the divine character: Hesed (Covenant Mercy) and Emet (Eternal Truth). According to Alexander Maclaren, these are the two wings upon which the soul rises to God. The word used for great or mighty regarding God’s mercy (Gavar) suggests that His grace is an irresistible force that triumphs over sin. By ending with Hallelujah, the Psalm links the history of Israel’s redemption to the future of the world’s salvation. It is a missionary mandate in poetic form, asserting that because God is eternally faithful to His word, the entire world has a reason to rejoice in Him. This shortest of Psalms carries the longest of reaches, extending from the temple in Jerusalem to the ends of the earth."
