        "content": "In the Talmud (Middot 2:5), the fifteen Songs of Ascents are linked to the fifteen steps leading from the Court of the Women to the Court of the Israelites in the Temple. Rashi, the preeminent Jewish commentator, interprets the sharp arrows in verse 4 as a direct metaphor for the evil tongue; just as an arrow kills from a distance, so does the slanderer harm those far away. Midrash Tehillim connects this psalm to the long exile of Israel, interpreting the lying lips as the deceptive promises of Gentile nations that sought to lead Israel away from the Torah. The Jewish tradition emphasizes that the tongue is the only weapon that can be used from within a house to kill someone outside, highlighting the treacherous nature of the speech described by the psalmist."
