        "title": "Brief Exposition",
        "content": "Psalm 120 begins the journey to Zion not with a shout of joy, but with a cry of pain. Verse 1 establishes the pattern of the believer’s life: distress leads to prayer, and prayer is met with the assurance of God’s hearing. The specific distress is the lying tongue (Verse 2). In a conservative biblical worldview, truth is the foundation of reality; therefore, deceit is a direct assault on the order of God.\n\nIn verses 3 and 4, the psalmist asks what should be done to a deceitful tongue. The answer is poetic justice. Since the tongue is like a sharp arrow and a burning fire, God will judge it with the warrior’s arrows and the eternal embers of the broom tree. This is not personal spite but a recognition of divine holiness.\n\nThe final section (Verses 5-7) describes the exhaustion of the believer living in a secular or hostile environment. Meshech and Kedar symbolize a world that rejects God’s covenant. The psalmist’s concluding remark is a profound summary of the believer’s experience: he speaks peace, but the world responds with war. This tension is what drives the pilgrim to leave the plains of the world and begin the ascent to the house of God. It teaches that the spiritual life often starts with a holy dissatisfaction with the lies of the present age."
