        "title": "Scholarly Voices",
        "content": "1. Charles Spurgeon, in The Treasury of David, emphasizes that the joy of the saints is a testimony to the world, noting that even the heathen were forced to acknowledge God's hand in the restoration of Israel.\n\n2. John Calvin observes that the term dream indicates the greatness of the miracle, suggesting it was so far beyond human expectation that the people feared it was a psychological illusion rather than a physical reality.\n\n3. Alexander Maclaren points out that verse 4 recognizes that the work started by God in the past must be completed by God in the present, comparing the returnees to a thin stream that needs the fullness of a flood.\n\n4. Derek Kidner notes the psychological realism of the psalm, where the initial laughter of return is followed by the hard work of sowing in tears, proving that spiritual restoration is both a divine gift and a human task.\n\n5. Joseph Alexander highlights that the Negeb imagery refers to the dry riverbeds that remain parched until the autumn rains suddenly transform them into rushing rivers, symbolizing a sudden shift from scarcity to abundance.\n\n6. Timothy Keller contrasts sudden restoration with the slower path of sowing in tears, showing that renewal may come like Negev streams or through patient prayer, repentance, and service that God will make fruitful.\n\n7. Alec Motyer sets the psalm in the tension of already and not yet, showing that the people have been saved, still need saving, and are taught to keep sowing while waiting for the final harvest.",
