        "content": "1. Charles Spurgeon, in The Treasury of David, highlights the resilience of the church, noting that the \"plowers\" may make long furrows, but they cannot kill the field. He remarks that the righteousness of God is the guarantee that the cords of the wicked will always be snapped just as they think they have secured their prey.\n\n2. John Calvin focuses on the \"youth\" of Israel, referring to the Egyptian bondage. He argues that the Church is always under the cross and that her survival is a perpetual miracle. He notes that God allows the wicked to plow the backs of the godly to test their patience but ultimately limits their power.\n\n3. Keil and Delitzsch emphasize the \"cutting of the cords\" in verse 4. They suggest this refers to the leather traces that connect the ox to the plow. By cutting these cords, God renders the \"plowing\" (persecution) impossible to continue, demonstrating His judicial sovereignty.\n\n4. Matthew Henry observes the contrast between the \"long furrows\" of the righteous man's suffering and the \"short life\" of the wicked man's prosperity. He notes that those who hate Zion are under a divine blight and will never gather a \"handful\" of lasting fruit.\n\n5. H.C. Leupold points out the nationalistic yet spiritual fervor of the psalm, asserting that it is a prayer for the vindication of God's chosen city, Zion, which represents the earthly dwelling place of His glory.\n\n6. Timothy Keller highlights Psalm 129 as resilient testimony: afflicted from youth, yet not destroyed. The plow-marks of suffering are real, but the Lord's righteousness cuts the cords of oppression and denies evil the final harvest.\n\n7. Alec Motyer observes that Israel's scars are real but not final, showing that long affliction cannot destroy the people whom the righteous Lord preserves and inviting perseverance without romanticizing pain.",
