        "title": "Christ in the Old Testament",
        "content": "1. The Scourged Back: The most striking Messianic connection is found in verse 3, \"The plowers plowed upon my back; they made long their furrows.\" Conservative scholars see this as a direct prophetic foreshadowing of the scourging of Jesus Christ (Matthew 27:26; Isaiah 50:6). The \"long furrows\" represent the wounds of the Savior who bore the stripes for His people.\n\n2. The Righteous Deliverer: Verse 4 declares, \"The Lord is righteous; He has cut the cords of the wicked.\" Christ is the Righteous One who, through His resurrection, broke the cords of death and the power of the enemy, delivering the Church from the \"plowing\" of Satan.\n\n3. The True Zion: Christ is the foundation and protector of Zion. Those who hate Him are like the grass on the roof—doomed to wither—while those rooted in Him partake in eternal life.",
