        "title": "Jewish Tradition",
        "content": "In the Midrash Tehillim, this psalm is interpreted as a summary of Israel's endurance throughout the four world empires. Rashi, the preeminent medieval commentator, focuses on the metaphor of the plowmen, identifying them as the various nations that have sought to destroy Israel’s identity and spiritual heritage. He emphasizes that despite the depth of the furrows made in their backs, the wicked were unable to complete their destructive work because God intervened. The Talmudic tradition occasionally links the imagery of the grass on the housetops to the transience of those who oppose the Torah, suggesting that their success is superficial and rootless, lacking the blessing of the Kohanim (priests)."
