        "title": "Brief Exposition",
        "content": "Psalm 134 brings the pilgrim’s journey to a triumphant and logical conclusion. It begins with an urgent appeal to the servants of the Lord—those Levites and priests whose duty it was to maintain the temple fire and the atmosphere of prayer during the night. They are urged to bless the Lord, transforming their duty into a delight. Verse 2 defines the physical and spiritual posture of this worship: the lifting of hands toward the holy place, symbolizing dependence, surrender, and the expectation of a divine response. The psalm concludes with a priestly response that turns the blessing back upon the pilgrim. The God who is the omnipotent Creator (Maker of heaven and earth) is also the localized God of the covenant (bless thee out of Zion). This ensures that as the pilgrim leaves the temple to return to daily life, he carries the supernatural favor and protection of the sanctuary with him into the world."
