        "content": "1. John Calvin notes that David fears his own heart more than he fears Saul, recognizing that external affliction often leads to internal bitterness and the temptation to retaliate sinfully.\n\n2. Charles Spurgeon, in The Treasury of David, argues that verse 5 is the mark of a truly humble man: one who would rather be smitten by a saint than flattered by a sinner.\n\n3. Matthew Henry emphasizes the evening sacrifice imagery, noting that as the day closes, the believer must settle accounts with God and seek protection for the night’s temptations.\n\n4. Keil and Delitzsch highlight the linguistic difficulty of verse 6 and 7, suggesting they describe the sudden judgment of the wicked leaders while the common people hear the sweet, gracious words of the psalmist once his integrity is proven.\n\n5. Alexander Maclaren observes that the central request is for the alignment of the will with God’s law, ensuring that even under trial, the psalmist does not practice wicked works or partake in the benefits of sin.\n\n6. Timothy Keller highlights Psalm 141 as a plea for holiness under pressure. The worshiper asks that prayer rise like incense, that his mouth be guarded, and that correction from the righteous be received as mercy rather than insult.\n\n7. Alec Motyer observes that prayer like incense is joined to a guarded mouth and teachable heart, showing that worship must shape speech and appetite and inviting correction as a mercy.",
