        "title": "Brief Exposition",
        "content": "Psalm 141 begins with an urgent plea for God to hear, framing prayer as a spiritual sacrifice that replaces the formal rituals David cannot currently access in the sanctuary. The heart of the psalm is a request for holiness; David asks God to garrison his mouth and heart against the gravitational pull of evil. He recognizes that the company one keeps and the words one speaks are the primary battlegrounds of the soul. He expresses a radical openness to the correction of the godly, viewing it as a blessing rather than an insult, contrasting this with the destructive dainties of the wicked. The psalm concludes with a shift from internal holiness to external safety. David fixes his eyes on Jehovah-God, the Sovereign Lord, trusting that while the wicked fall into their own nets and traps, he will pass over them in safety by the grace of God. This text serves as a manual for the believer who is under pressure to conform to a godless society and needs divine help to remain untainted."
