        "title": "Historical Background",
        "content": "Conservative scholars such as J.J. Stewart Perowne and Franz Delitzsch align on a post-exilic date for Psalm 147. The specific mentions of building up Jerusalem and gathering the outcasts of Israel in verse 2 strongly suggest the era of Nehemiah. The internal evidence of verse 13 regarding the strengthening of the bars of the gates points toward the successful completion of Jerusalem’s walls in 444 B.C. This psalm served as a liturgical celebration of God’s restorative power following the return from Babylonian captivity, emphasizing that the physical reconstruction of the city was a manifestation of divine favor."
