        "content": "Psalm 148 is widely recognized by conservative scholars such as Franz Delitzsch and Charles Spurgeon as a post-exilic hymn, likely composed during the Second Temple period. Its placement in the final Hallelujah cycle (Psalms 146-150) suggests it was intended for the liturgical restoration of Israel following the return from Babylonian captivity. Conservative tradition often links the spirit of this Psalm to the era of Ezra and Nehemiah, where the reconstructed walls and temple prompted a renewed sense of cosmic order under the sovereignty of Yahweh. The Psalm reflects a period of intense theological reflection on God as both the transcendent Creator and the immanent Redeemer of Israel."
